segments.text: This is an interview with Steve Lambert by Matt Vogel on November 25th, 1988 at Gulf Coast Sailing Center in Clear Lake Shores, Texas.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the Vietnam War, I am going to donate this tape to Texas A&M Oral History Collection and the University Archives.
Is that all right with you, Steve?
Fine.
Thank you very much.
Steve, we'll first start off with when and where were you born?
I was born in Houston, Texas, December the 8th, 1950.
And where were you raised up?
I was raised in Houston through most of my life, and then actually moved to Pasadena in the early 60s.
So I went through high school in Pasadena area and grew up in Pasadena through my teenage years.
Were any of your relatives in the military, and if so, when and where?
Yeah, my father was in the Air Force, went in right at the end of World War II and spent some time in Germany.
And then my brother had joined the Air Force about a year prior to me being drafted into the service.
And he was in the States most of the time, although he did do a tour in Thailand, didn't actually fly, did ground support services in Thailand.
What did you know about the Vietnam War before you joined?
Not really a whole lot other than what TV and media had put out.
I did very little reading about it.
Basically, I understood it was a, quote, conflict and not really a war, and that we were there as mediators initially trying to basically support the local government and
You know, also the French had stepped in, I understood, and they were also in that type of a mediator type effect.
But it became a full-scale war from what we understood.
And, you know, until I actually got there and saw what it was, I really didn't know, you know, what the real thing was.
You know, basically the media had played it up more than what it really was at times.
And then at times they really didn't have the truth
thing either.
Once you get there you have to form your own opinion of what you're looking at.
That leads to one question that I did forget to write down and that is when did you go to high school and when did you go to college?
I went to Sam Rayburn High School in Pasadena, graduated in 1969.
Next year I went to one semester, started school at the University of Houston and did not finish that full semester.
And likewise, I was married and was basically to work full time.
And therefore, my number got thrown into the lottery and I was drafted.
So if I would have stayed in school, I would not have been drafted, probably.
When were you drafted?
I was drafted in 1970, or actually 69, actually.
And shortly, right as soon as I got out of the...
thing that my name immediately went in and my number was picked.
So I actually went to my orientation type thing in October and November of 69 and went in in 1970.
And I want to say January, February of 70, yeah.
Right.
At what basis were you trained and what type of training did you receive?
Initially, I went into the Army.
I went to Fort Polk, Louisiana.
I went through what they call their basic training, which was more or less a military courtesy type stuff, your general hand-to-hand combat, military weapons training.
We were trained on the M16, light weapons, your hand grenades.
your first aid, some military tactics and stuff like that.
We had very little other than our normal calisthenics, outsource, outdoor type activities.
We did do one overnight stint where we basically did a maneuver or a bivouac where we went out and spent the night in the woods one night.
We did a lot of marching and running and stuff like that, but the actual overnight stuff, we only did one overnight thing in basic training.
By going in January and February, it was very cold and we would, in Louisiana, we did actually snow on us a couple of times while we were there.
So the training was done in fairly cold conditions at that time.
And then shortly after that, I was tested at the end that I was picked for what they called AIT or Advanced Infantry Training.
And my MOS at that time was given me as what was considered an 11 Bravo.
which is infantry.
From what I was told, my basis was picked because of my answers on my questionnaire, you know, that they gave me or whatever on my testing.
And I literally did battery of testing for probably three or four days in a row of all sorts of tests and questions and stuff like that.
And I have a gut feeling I was picked mainly because of my experience with guns, hunting as a kid,
fishing, outdoors activities, stuff like that, and I answered it truthfully that I'd done a lot of that, so maybe that's why I was picked.
I really don't know.
There was also a lot of other people or guys that were picked that had never been in the woods in their life or even held a gun, so I don't know if that was the basis, but it might have been.
My AIT was spent also in Fort Polk, Louisiana.
It was more along the military tactics
more weapon handling.
What kind of weapons that were different?
Well, we went, stepped up from the M16 to the M60, the 20 millimeter, did the pistol, .45 caliber pistol, did a .50 caliber machine gun.
We shot a weapon called a wall, which was a light anti-tank weapon.
We got to shoot that a few times.

got more proficient in the M16, a lot more different training, not just shooting at fixed targets, but moving targets and, you know, actually moving where you run and shoot and fall down or run and shoot and fall down.
So more activity from that standpoint there, but it was still strictly a target type thing.
AIT, we did two or three different BIVWACs, but still there was not that much overnight training or anything really jungle warfare or anything that way.
It was pretty basic

straightforward so in other words we weren't trained to go to Vietnam we were just trained in a standard military procedure where we could have gone anywhere in the world whether it be you know Saudi Arabia or Germany or Russia or wherever you know from that standpoint so there was no specific jungle warfare training at that time.
Were you ever taught Vietnamese?
No.
Did you go to any other schools?
Well after the AIT I was
elected or picked to go to what I was considered shake and bake school or NCO or noncommissioned officer school where I would become an E5, which is a sergeant.
When I went home on leave, I expected that to be my orders.
When I returned and my orders came in, I was not picked and I was sent to a what they call tracker school.
Initially went in and worked with dogs and then I
went from there and did visual tracking.
This type of stuff was all done in the jungle of Georgia area.
We were at Fort Garden and Fort Benning, Georgia.
This was done more in the heat of the summer type thing as it progressed through my training basically.
It got a lot hotter.
We would spend literally days out in the woods with our rucksacks, which were the same thing in Vietnam.
We had Vietnam-issue clothing.
We had carried M16s, and we were trained basically at that time more of a jungle warfare type thing.
We were trained at that time also by veterans from Vietnam, where in their basic in AIT,
there was no actual Vietnam veterans.
They were your lifers, if you want to put it that way.
They were good men, but they were not veterans of Vietnam.
They were strictly your lifer type guys that might have been in World War II even, you know, been around forever.
Korean Warfare or something like that.
We basically learned more or less how to observe the different movements
in the woods and they would set up ambushes for us and trip wires, booby traps, stuff we would actually see in Vietnam basically.
So this was geared towards Vietnam?
So this was geared directly towards Vietnam and tracking and of course at that time I did not have orders to go to Nam although that's what I was being trained for.
And this went on for six weeks.
And I would say at least five of the six weeks I was in the woods.
So it was continuous intensive training in the jungle.
How many people were being trained at the same time you were there?
At that particular location, there was only about 18 to 20 of us.
And out of those 18 to 20, I'd say at least a dozen of them were dog handlers.
So there's very few visual trackers.
So more or less, I was elected.
or felt as an elite type thing because of my abilities.
I guess a lot of it had to do with coloring.
We were color tested as far as color blindness.
And evidently your leaves and your trees and stuff like this, as we were taught, they turn one way or the other.
The colors change just a little bit.
And this is something that is very, very hard for an average person to pick up.
But
As we were taught, we could see where a guy had walked through and just brushed the leaves and they had changed and stuff like that.
So this was a very unique thing to pick up.
And of course, there's all kinds of things to look for as far as the movement of the twigs and even the sounds from the birds and stuff like that.
If somebody had walked through the woods, a lot of times you can tell just by listening whether somebody's been through there or not.
So there's lots of different things you can look for and you're taught to see and pick up.
And then maybe that was also my experience of hunting

As a kid, I grew up hunting and shooting and stuff like that, but that particular training, in my feeling now, kind of looking back on it, probably saved my life many times because of what I was taught in that particular type of training.
Okay, this leads to the next question, and that is, please briefly describe your Vietnamese tour of beauty.
Okay, just briefly.
I went in, was assigned to an infantry unit.
We were company squads, you know, leveled down through that.
I was 101st Airborne.
At that time, we worked around the military zone, the DMZ.
Did you go through airborne school?
No.
I did actually go through jump school as far as I never...
I did... Yeah, I guess I did in a way.
When I was at my...
Visual tracker thing, we went through a modified school.
I did not go through a full airborne blown airborne thing.
When we were at Fort Benning, part of the training we did there was jump.
We rappelled and jumped.
But it was not what would be considered a full airborne school.
And this was part of our training because we were expected to possibly jump out of choppers.
And so we jumped out of choppers in a modified condition rather than a full blown C-130 or something like that.
Yes and no.
I did not get qualified 100% as airborne, but I did jump.
I got my wings or whatever you want to call it from that standpoint, but that was part of my visual tracker school.
I could actually jump and rappel.
We did a lot of rappelling, actually more rappelling than jumping, but we did this at Fort Benning, Georgia when we were at Benning.
Anyway, when we were 101st or
Our main mission there basically was we would go and work around the DMZ more or less securing areas and more or less observation type thing rather than assault.
We would just basically go out, observe the enemy, pull back and watch them more or less rather than a massive takeover of any areas.
We at that time were in the process of turning over the area to the local Arvin South Vietnamese Army
So we did a lot of working with them.
I spent approximately six months in that area working with them.
They turned it over to them.
Because I'd only been in the area for six months or in Vietnam for six months, rather than being able to go home with that particular unit, I was transferred to the 1st Cav.
And when they sent me to the 1st Cav, I was fortunate enough to get my MOS changed and upgraded to 11 Foxtrot or 11F, which is intelligence.
I went in with them and I got working basically at that time it was an Air Mac unit which basically was air mobile rather than the track, half tracks or tanks or anything, the cavalry type thing.
We flew rather than rode in track.
And we would fly into an area and basically do the same type thing.
I was working through intelligence and tracking enemy movement
And we'd record it basically that way.

And I did do some individualized missions type thing where we'd go in with like three or four guys and be dropped into a listening post area and just sit there and listen and observe and see who was there and what was there.
Or I'd go in after an airstrike or something like that and just kind of see what was there and check it out.
And then they'd pull us back out.
So we were just basically observing there again rather than any kind of an attack mode or anything.
We were just there looking and observing more than fighting.
although there was several encounters where we had contact and fighting and stuff like that, so I didn't totally miss what was going on.
But our main primary mission was basically observation rather than assaulting.
That was with the 101st and the intelligence, too?
Yes, exactly, both of them.
Were they both at I-Corps?
Yes.
What year did you go in, or what month did you go into Vietnam?
I went into Vietnam in, let's see,
It was 1970, and I'm going to say May.
I can't remember the exact date, but it was in the middle of May.
After your track and school.
Yeah, exactly.
And then I stayed there all through that year.
No, it couldn't have been that early, because I got out February.
So it had to have been later that December, not May.
No, it was later.
Let me think about that now.
I stayed, yeah, it was, it was, it was, it was Clowry closer to September because I remember more when I got out and I got out around February.
And I stayed there, you know, for right at 14 months.
So backtrack from there, you can probably figure out exactly what it was.
So you got out on February 72?
Right, right, exactly.
Did you receive any training, any further training, once you stepped down the shores of Vietnam?
No.
Okay.
No.
So all your training was in the States?
Yes, definitely.
Okay, this is going to switch over.
You did mention about what your purpose was there as far as being observational.
Right.
And was there an overall strategy that you could see that you were being part of?
I mean, what was the overall strategy as far as the U.S. forces were concerned?
Right.
Initially, when I was with the 101st the first six months, our overall strategy was to basically secure that particular area.
When you say area, is that the rural area?
The rural area around the DMZ at that time.

The closest city that we worked out of was a place called Fubai, and we worked off of all types of fire bases, which are basically a command post in the jungle or in the swamp lands or rice paddies, as you have it that way.
But the artillery guys would set up these fire bases, and we would work out of a fire base, which would be a secure area, and then we'd run our missions out of these fire bases.
We'd either walk out of them or be flown out.
And we would just basically go out and patrol a certain area, set up a night ambush, and secure that area.
So more or less we were in a police state where we were just holding the area and securing it.
Then we started working with the South Vietnamese, and they would actually go out at the same time with us and do the same thing.
So if anything, we were training the South Vietnamese to maintain their hold on the country that we had established.
By the time I got there,

basically the country was pretty much areas were designated that we had and there was it was just a I don't know sniper attacks and small you know companies would would hit us and stuff like that there was never a major offensives most of those that all happened in the late 60s early 60s late 60s by the time the 70s came along there was really no major overruns or major offensives there's a few in the country but it was pretty much just small
contacts here and there.
There was no major uproar anywhere, basically.
Right.
Describe some of the operations that you went on that worked rather well.
Well... Or if that's even applicable.
Well, basically, you know, just an average operation or whatever we would do, say, as a company, they'd send us out in squads.
We had like 12-man squads.
Okay.
Okay.
We would be given an area on the map, and we would be basically told that it was reported in this particular area on these particular trails there would be enemy movement.
So we would be sent out to go out and secure that particular area, set up a night ambush, and more or less at that time, either if they came, go ahead and shoot them or try to take them captive.
They wanted live captives so they could, you know, intelligence purposes.
That was the whole thing.
But we were to basically, if there was enemy movement in the area, we would try to eliminate that movement and re-secure that area.
Okay?
So we would be flown out to a certain area, be dropped, and we'd have to walk usually what they call clicks and kilometers.
We would have to walk probably five or six clicks through the jungle to this particular area, and it would be done in a very quiet, you know, mode.

Usually on a two- to three-day mission we carried what was called light to fight, so we had very light rucks with almost nothing in them, you know, just our water and a couple of days' rations and, you know, our ammo, and that was about it.
So we didn't carry a lot of gear on a short mission like that.

We'd go out in the area, we'd find where the enemy had been moving, and a lot of this was left up to the sergeant and lieutenant type thing, you know, basically through the compass headings and stuff like that.
They would actually get us there.
And then once we got there, we would set up our ambush site with our claymores, and we'd set up a perimeter getting ready for the people to walk through or something like that.
And then we would just sit there at night, and we usually carried at least one starlight scope in the squad, and we'd just pass that around to the guys that was on watch at that time.
And if anything ever came in, you'd always click your claymores and blow them, and then everybody would open up fire at that time.
And then you'd call in people the next morning or whatever.
If you had to have an airstrike, you'd call in something
A lot of times we would call in the Navy up on the DMC.
There was one instance where we did call in B-52 strike, and we pulled back and we found a bunker complex.
And we pulled back.
They did a B-52 strike on the bunker complex.
Then we went back in to check it out after they dropped the stuff on the complex that way.
Did you ever bring in any artillery spotters?
Yes, we did.
We really, yeah, we used them off the fire bases every once in a while.
We found that they were not as accurate as even, you know, the most accurate would be the Navy.
Those guys was always on the money.
You know, we'd call it and they'd hit it and we'd say, you know, add 100, they'd add 100 and be right on the money.
The Army guys, they just didn't seem to be there all the time.
You know, you never could count on them.
And...
You'd call for them and call for them, and sometimes you'd get it and sometimes you wouldn't.
But the Navy was always there.
What do you think that happened?
Do you have any ideas?
I really don't know.

There was a prevalent amount of drugs in the fire bases, and you don't want to blame it all on drugs, but the guys in the fire bases really did a lot of drugs, so it's very possible they just couldn't care less.
They were in there doing their thing.
Or it's possible they just weren't properly trained to hit where you wanted them to hit.
Did they ever lose some short rounds on y'all?
Oh, yes.
Were y'all ever in danger?
Oh, yeah.
They hit all around us.
That was a common thing.
But, I mean, we learned to expect it.
We'd always dig in, and we would pull back pretty good ways if we could.
Now, one time we had quite a bit of enemy around us.
We didn't know how many because we were getting sniper shots from all around us.
So we called in a local artillery type thing, and we basically gave them our position.
and said, hit around us, because we want them to shoot and knock down the enemy around us.
And they came in, and they hit within 30, 40 yards of us, just right on top of us, which was good.
And then we said, add here, take there, to try to move it around us.
And they did fairly good with something like that.
But in a situation, you never knew where they were going to land.
Where on the Navy, you could almost count on pinpointing.
If you gave them the right coordinates, they hit it.
It was up to the guy that was calling it.
And usually in the company, there would be one or two, you know, trained artillery guys that would go with us on a mission.
And those would be the guys that would actually call it.
Now, if it was just a squad, usually there would be a lieutenant, a couple of sergeants, and then the regular PFCs, you know, normal guys.
And usually the lieutenant would try to do it if he had enough knowledge.
And if not, one of the good sergeants would do it.
We went through lieutenants quite often, and those guys, you know, they'd come and go quite a bit, so it was... We'll get to those later.
Yeah, it was a situation where usually the sergeant was most qualified to call in all terrorists.
You mentioned that you were essentially, that essentially y'all were turning the war over to the local ARVN units.
Right.
Did you take ARVN out on any of these missions?
If so, describe your interactions with ARVN.
Well, basically what we would do...

a lot of times rather than take them with us we would rendezvous with them at a specific point and then we would proceed at that time and set up an ambush or something like that or just patrol a certain area with them and this was all done during the daylight hours and we did not like to travel with them that much because they were not really quiet
You know, for say, when you're walking through the woods, you know, I want your pots and pans jingling and the guys running their mouth all the time.
You want to walk quiet.
And they would always talk and they would smoke.
And, you know, they really, like, they could care less.
You know, like, they were drafted.
They didn't want to be there either, just like we didn't want to be there.
But they just really weren't, there wasn't a fear, I don't think, in their lives like there was in ours.
And so a lot of times, you know, the guys, especially the colored guys, they just say, man, I ain't going out.
Those guys are going to be there, you know.

But we would go out and set up ambush with them and show them how to set up the claymores and show them how to secure an area and basically try to teach them and instruct them how to do these maneuvers we were doing.
And then we would more or less just kind of send like a squad of guys would go with one of their companies.
We might be 12.
They might have 25 or 30.
And we'd go out on the mission just as observers with them sometimes and let them do it all.
And we would assist them if they needed assisting, you know, that sort of thing.
And, you know, that pretty much is.
Did their officers call the shots?
Oh, yeah, definitely.
Yes, definitely.
Definitely.
Yeah, it was a strictly chain of command type thing, you know, same type deal.
But they just didn't have the discipline that our military had.
And, you know, not that our military was the best in the world by any means, but the chain of command is definitely there.
And
you know, it was followed pretty closely over there.
And, you know, people depended on the other guy to stay alive.
And there was times when you, you know, you couldn't cook because of the smell from food would basically alert the enemy.
You couldn't even hardly open a can.
We used a hand can opener called a P-38.
And if you're sitting there moving it back and forth around the can, you had the noise when you're opening the can.
And you couldn't even open a can of food because the noise would just echo through the woods.
You couldn't talk.
And the Arvin guys, they did it all.
I mean, you know, they do everything in the world.
You know, they're pots and pans and cooking their rice.
I mean, you could smell an Arvin camp, you know, a mile away.
So, you know, it was a situation where we did not really like to work with them that much.
And, you know, we were basically, like I said, just trying to, at that time with 101st, trying to get the area secure so we could turn it over to them.
And we were just more or less in a stand-down mode for those six months.

Although there was quite a bit of contact, we'd go out and actually come in contact with 25 or 30 of the enemy and have shooting back and forth and basically people would be killed and stuff like that.
My original squad of 12 guys
there's nine of them that did not come back.
And so there's only three of us that made it back.
So, I mean, you know, there was a lot of guys that would get killed, and the newbies would seem to go first.

You know, they just, a lot of guys coming out of basic training or AIT who had no knowledge of the jungle, like I wouldn't have had if I wouldn't have had my tracker school, would come in and, you know, they'd just be bopping down a trail and get blown away or step on a landmine or tripwire or something like that.

And usually booby traps or snipers killed the majority of them rather than major offensive, you know, it was more or less a they'd wound one guy and take two guys to carry him out type deal, you know, that sort of thing.
Did it seem like that, well, I don't want to get to the enemy yet.
Let me finish one last question.
Sure, no problem.
And that is were there any effective Arvin units that you knew of or worked with?
Yeah, there were some that were better, yes.
We always worked with different units all the time, and
There were some units that did seem to be better than others, yes.
There's no doubt about it.
It's just like any, I guess, anything.
It's the personnel that you're working with.
But there were some units that seemed to be a lot more trained and better at what they were doing, you know, that way.
But overall, to pick up on what you said earlier, but overall, do you think most of them didn't really care?
They were pretty much overall drafted just like I was drafted, and they didn't want to be there.
And they could care less who their government was or what, you know, from that standpoint.
So the overall feeling at that time in that area, they just could care less.
Were they unappreciative of y'all?
No, not really.
I think they were appreciative because we fed them, we clothed them, we gave them their weapons and their ammunition.
And, you know, to them it was great.
I mean, they had food, they had clothing, they had rifles.

They were appreciative from that point, but, you know, it was a situation, you know, even, you know, the Altieri and stuff like that, we'd walk up with firebases that we'd built for them and, you know, turn around and leave, and a month later we might have to go back in there and take it back again after the Arvids had done let the enemy overrun it and take everything.
And we'd go back and it'd just totally be overrun and gone, and the Arvids would lose it all, and they'd just turn, tell, and run or be all killed.
So they just, they weren't fighters, and they really weren't interested in securing anything.
Although they did want what we would give them.
They had their hands out all day long, but they really didn't care about it after they got it, or try to take care of it, basically.
I guess they weren't too interested in the land as long as they got the food.
Yeah, we fed them and clothed them, and they were pleased.
They loved it.
It has been said that the enemy controlled the night, and we controlled the day.
Did this apply to the areas you worked in?
Pretty much.
How did it affect the way y'all operated?
We very, very seldom ever moved at night because that really was when they moved.
And they were experts at jungle warfare where we were not.
Even with their training?
Well, I probably could have felt pretty good.
Now, some of the special forces and stuff like that were really trained to move.
I know some of the Marines and stuff like that, but your, quote, basic Army infantry unit,
was not trained like that.
They had no warfare as far as guerrilla warfare or anything like that.

Now, your special forces guys and stuff like that, they were very capable of going in and moving around at night and being very good with the camouflage and stuff like that where they could do their thing, but your special forces were the only ones that really could do that.
The general consensus of the Army over there, your average infantry grunt, they called them,
They could not do that safely.
There was just too many numbers of them, and they were too clumsy and loud, and they just didn't have the training to move around at night.
Where your enemy, which I found more of your what I would call Viet Cong rather than NVA.
So you didn't come in that much contact?
Not that many contact with the regular Army.
Now, we did see some, but not in numbers at all, very, very limited.
I guess the most numbers we ever saw were actually Viet Cong.
And those guys were their typical pajamas, your black-type suit, you know, and their little hats.
And they carried the AK-47s and, you know, brass and tubes on their back, you know, of the food and, you know, very little anything.
They could move very, very quickly and quietly through the jungle, and you never even know they were there.
But it was a situation where, yes, they definitely controlled the night.
We would set up ambushes and wait for them.
Where if we moved, we would usually run into a sniper or something and be shot at.
They would always see us before we'd see them if we were moving.
Whereas if we were actually sitting and waiting for them, then usually we were a lot more effective setting them up in ambush rather than us actually moving.
Did you set up any ambushes?
You didn't set up any ambushes when you were with the 1st Cav and with the intelligence.
Yes, we did set some up, but not near in the capacity that we did up on the DMZ.
The primary purpose of the 1st Cav?
Where I was was just observation.
Okay, and intelligence.
Intelligence reporting, yes, exactly, because when I was intelligence now,
There was a couple of times we did actually go up and we set up a couple of ambushes because we wanted to actually see how many people there were.
And rather than try to sit there and be quiet and let them go by, we felt it would be better to go ahead and ambush them and try to take some prisoners for intelligent purposes.
Did you ever take prisoners successfully?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes, definitely.
Okay.
That was our main purpose when we did do an ambush was to take them alive so we could go back and actually have them interrogated.
And several times we would have prisoners and take them back.
When we did do that, they would fly out and pick them up real quick.
And I did several times.

I would actually, if I was in the rear and they called in and said somebody had prisoners, I would fly out with my training and act as a guard basically to take the prisoners back to the bases to have them interrogated.
With their training?
Well, because of my being a, quote, infantry soldier.

See, a lot of these guys in the rear area were only clerks and typists, and they had gone through a basic training, but they had not been trained in any kind of warfare whatsoever, where they didn't leave the fire bases.
They stayed right there in the secured area of the fire base and never really went into the jungle.
So there's...
all different sides of the military that were there, you know, that they never actually got out and fought.

You know, they might have gotten shot at or had a firebomb thrown at them in the Saigon or something like that, but they actually did get out in the jungle and, you know, didn't see warfare or anything like that.
But we definitely did take prisoners when we could, and they wanted prisoners.
Of course, they wanted headcount, and there was a couple of colonels, you know, they just thrived on shooting people and cutting their ears off.
This was not really...

it was obvious that that was dead villagers, old papa-san, so to say, mama-san dead villagers that y'all counted?

And we did this for a couple of reasons.
Number one,
because a lot of times the enemy would bury stuff in grave sites, and we would be looking for their caches, which was basically food and or weapons.

And in the respect that we were basically on the mode, we were pulling out and leaving that particular area, we would go in.
If we found a village in a grave site that looked like it was fresh, we would dig it up and inspect it to see what it was.

you know, you kind of say, really, were they or weren't they?

Did you ever get the feeling like the enemy was every Vietnamese that you saw and everyone?

And during the daytime, you could drive into the villages and

basically shop if you want to tell me you know from that i mean we really didn't do that but i mean they had stuff you could go in there and like as you go to bars and drank and stuff like that and their prostitution was very prominent there there was a lot of girls you know you can always go get a girl get a you know a layer or whatever you want to call it that way they had real strict curfews at night and they said do not spend the night in the villages get back to the to secure camp

Where'd he go?

you know, they found him in the village, all his throat was cut or something like that, you know, that sort of thing.

And, you know, if they...
gave you any indication they were going to run or shoot or do anything.
You shot first and asked questions later.

The villagers didn't need to be in the jungle.

When they traveled, they traveled on the open roads or on the big trails and open area.

With your experience with the 101st and the 1st Cav as intelligence, did the VC mainly move at night?
Yes, definitely.
They obviously knew.
Yeah, they moved at night and they were very safe and secure.
Now, there's always exceptions to the rule, but 90% of the movement was at night.

In my intelligence, especially, we had several different listening devices and a thing called Red Slayer, which was a heat-sensoring device where the airplanes would actually fly over a certain area, and it would send up a radiation or whatever effect from the body heat of the humans.
And they could actually more or less count how many people was down there and everything, so they could see them moving in particular areas.
And you plot this movement over like three or four days, and you could actually see them moving down a trail.
you know, in an area.
And we could send in a company or a squad ahead of them knowing that was the direction they were going on this particular trail and set up an ambush and wait for them.
Did that work well?
It worked quite well.
But it was a situation they seemed to know where the enemy were all the time.
If they wanted to end the war, they probably could have sent massive troops in there and killed them all and got it over with.
But they never seemed to want to do it.
It was always little hit and miss ambush type stuff.
So in my mind, after getting into intelligence, I don't know why they did what they did.

You know, I just don't understand it because, you know, the area that I worked in, especially with the first Cav, with the intelligence part, we knew almost every enemy movement that happened almost on a daily basis.
And we could have gone in there and wiped them out at any time.
Now, would these have been NVA troop movements?
No, this was all Viet Cong, yeah, V.C., yeah.

Yeah.

Yes, definitely, yeah.

That's right.

and through your experience, how did you feel about the VC as a fighting unit?
Were they an effective fighting unit?
Were they well-disciplined?
Or were they a poor fighting unit?

I felt there was the actual Viet Cong, per se, were more of a very well-trained jungle warfare type hit and
run type deal.
They were not a massive discipline military organization by any means.
It was a hit and miss.
They would come out and hit you and run.
Hit you and run.
And all they would do would be like stick a thorn in your side.
They just hurt you, but they wouldn't kill you.
And they would more or less, like I said, they would shoot one guy and take two guys to carry him away type deal.
And they did this through their booby traps,
They do this through their sniper attacks, their mortar attacks in the villages and the fire bases and stuff like that.
And it was more or less just a hit and miss.
The NVA, well, okay, the NVA, on the other hand, they were more of a disciplined military type thing.
And they would travel in squads and companies similar to what we did.
And they would set up, and they would actually, like if they were to overrun a fire base or something, they would actually have it come in waves.
I mean, just like a normal military procedure and stuff like that.
So they were very, very disciplined military-wise, chain of command, the whole nine yards.
with the uniforms and the weapons and, you know, the backing and stuff there, they had good training.
That type of thing I didn't see that much of, although I did see one or two instances where they actually tried, attempted to overrun a fire base in some of the hours that we were on.

Up in the DMZ or Fire Base Gibraltar was the name of one of them that I was on.

It depended on more or less how long we were going to be out in the field.
